<DOC><DOCNO> AP880917-0042 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 0321EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Colombia     09-17 0375</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Colombia,0388</SECOND><HEAD>Rebels Burst Into Court Building and Free Five Comrades; OneHostage Killed</HEAD><BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Armed left-wing rebels burst into afederal court building, freed five jailed comrades and abducted ajudge's assistant, who was later found shot to death, police said.   They said the guerrillas fired automatic weapons as they enteredthe building in the town of Buga, 160 miles southwest of Bogota.   Police said they captured two of the guerrillas freed in theattack after an hourlong chase. The body of the hostage was foundbeside a highway outside of town, police said.   They did not report any other casualties or further elaborate.   In other developments, leftist rebels freed 22 governmentsoldiers and policemen captured in a northwestern Colombia raidlast month and also released two Colombian geologists seized inanother attack, the government and military announced.   The soldiers and policemen freed Friday had been taken prisonerAug. 23 by guerrillas of the People's Liberation Army and theColombian Revolutionary Armed Forces during a joint attack on thetown of Saiza.   A statement from President Virgilio Barcos's office said aone-day cease-fire had been arranged so the captives could bereleased in the Uraba region, about 300 miles northwest of Bogota.   Two of the government troopers had been wounded in the rocketand mortar attack on the police station in Saiza, Gen. Jesus Ariassaid in an interview with the radio station RCN. He did notelaborate.   The two geologists released Thursday were among five who workedwith coal companies and were kidnapped Aug. 20 by rebels of anotherguerrilla group, the National Liberation Army, or ELN.   Rebels freed the two geologists in an arranged meeting with agroup of reporters in the city of Bucaramanga, 200 miles northeastof Bogota.   An ELN statement said the three other geologists would bereleased soon.   A Defense Ministry communique released Friday said 1,174 peoplehave been killed this year in guerrilla attacks and battles betweenrebels and security forces.   It listed the slain as 499 guerrillas, 378 civilians and 297policemen and soldiers.   The ministry has reported 2,037 people were killed last year infighting involving rebels, government forces and civilians caughtin the violence.</TEXT></DOC>